# LLM-assisted development (full reference)

The **always-on** rule **`llm-development-guidelines.mdc`** holds the mandatory post-change workflow, merge gates, and concise PR/CHANGELOG rules. This file expands: per-tool lint detail, hook lists, full PR/commit templates, command catalogs, best practices, and common failures.

**Hypothesis / Ghostwriter:** See [tests/README.md](../../tests/README.md) (property-based tests).

## Purpose

This file is specifically designed for LLM assistants (like Claude, ChatGPT, etc.) working on this codebase. It provides clear instructions on:

- Required workflow after making code changes
- Linting tools and their configurations
- Pre-commit hooks usage
- Quick reference commands
- Best practices to avoid pipeline failures
- Ask before drafting GitHub PR text so iterative work is not noisy; **`CHANGELOG.md` is updated in that same PR-drafting step**, not on every intermediate fix

## Upstream Pulp (domain reference)

**[pulpproject.org](https://pulpproject.org/)** is the official Pulp project site: repositories, content types, REST API shapes, plugins, and user or admin docs. Consult it when reasoning about Pulp server behavior or API semantics that this repo’s client implements. Copy-paste commands and general repo conventions: **`AGENTS.md`**. Konflux call sites, config paths, and **`upload`** contracts for downstream pipelines: **`CLAUDE.md`** (and `.cursor/rules/konflux-ecosystem.mdc`).

## GitHub PR description (ask first; generate on confirmation)

To avoid dumping long PR boilerplate on every turn—especially while debugging—**do not** automatically paste a full PR body at the end of every response.

When the turn involved **substantive code or repository changes** that could become a PR, **end with a short question**, for example: *“Are you ready for a paste-ready GitHub PR description?”* or *“Want me to draft the PR title/body next?”*

- **Only after the user confirms** (in the same thread or a follow-up message), provide a paste-ready PR description **and**, if applicable, apply the `CHANGELOG.md` edits for that PR in the same turn.

**PR template (mandatory structure):** The file **`.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`** defines the canonical body. When generating paste-ready PR text, **reproduce that skeleton exactly**:

1. `## Summary` — replace the HTML comment with the real summary (what/why).
2. `## How to test` — replace the comment with concrete commands or steps.
3. `## Checklist` — keep all three `- [ ]` lines **unchanged** (contributor checks them in GitHub).
4. `## Notes for reviewers` — optional content; delete the HTML comment or add notes.

Do **not** rename sections, omit the checklist, or use a different heading outline unless the user explicitly overrides. Extra prose is fine **inside** those sections only.

When you deliver it in chat, you may prefix with `### PR description (GitHub)` for clarity, but the block the user pastes into GitHub should start with `## Summary` per the template.

When you do generate it, write in **complete sentences** with good grammar.

**Suggested commit message:** When the user asks for a PR message or confirms PR materials, also provide a **paste-ready `git commit` message** under `### Suggested commit message` using this shape (subject line as conventional commit; blank line; then trailers):

```
<type(scope): short description>

Assisted-By: <name of the assistant used — e.g. Cursor, Composer, Claude>
Signed-off-by: <human author — use the contributor’s GitHub/git identity>
```

- **Assisted-By:** The **agent or product** used for the change (e.g. `Cursor`, `Composer`, `Claude`, `ChatGPT`), not a person’s name unless the user specifies otherwise.
- **Signed-off-by:** The **human** who owns the commit — typically the same as `git config user.name` and `git config user.email` (often matching their [GitHub noreply or verified email](https://docs.github.com/en/account-and-profile/setting-up-and-managing-your-personal-account-on-github/managing-email-preferences/setting-your-commit-email-address)). Do **not** invent a real email; use a clear placeholder such as `Jane Doe <jane@users.noreply.github.com>` and tell the author to replace it with their identity, or run `git interpret-trailers` / edit before committing.

**`CHANGELOG.md`**: Do **not** add or edit `CHANGELOG.md` while iterating on a fix or feature mid-conversation unless the user explicitly asks. When the user confirms they want PR materials, **then** add `[Unreleased]` entries (if the change is user-facing or notable per CONTRIBUTING) **as part of drafting the PR**—either by editing the file in that turn or listing exact changelog lines in the PR draft for the author to paste.

**Skip** the question when there are no repo edits (pure Q&A, planning only) or the user has clearly said they only want a small fix with no PR.

## Pull requests (GitHub): 100% diff coverage merge gate

**CRITICAL**: In GitHub, a pull request **cannot be merged** unless **diff coverage is 100%** on the lines introduced or modified by that PR (branch vs base). CI reports this as diff / pull-request coverage (for example via `diff-cover` against the merge base).

- Treat **every changed line** in the PR as needing an executing test (unit or integration) on CI’s view of the diff.
- Project-wide coverage thresholds (for example 85% total) are separate; **the merge blocker is 100% on the PR diff**, not “good enough” overall coverage.
- If CI fails with incomplete diff coverage, add or extend tests until the PR diff is fully covered—do not rely on “nearby” or incidental coverage from unrelated code.

## Required Workflow After Making Changes

**CRITICAL**: Always follow this workflow after making any code changes:

1. **Make your code changes** - Implement the requested feature or fix
2. **Run linters immediately** - Don't wait, run linters right after changes:
   ```bash
   make lint
   ```
3. **Fix any linting errors** - Address all issues before proceeding
4. **Format code** - Ensure code is properly formatted:
   ```bash
   make format
   ```
5. **Run pre-commit until everything passes** - Loop until hooks are fully green:
   ```bash
   pre-commit run --all-files
   ```
   If any hook fails, fix **all** reported issues, then run `pre-commit run --all-files` again. **Repeat** until one full run completes with **no failures** (not a fixed number of runs—keep going until clean). A second run after fixes is the minimum; often more iterations are needed while fixing.
6. **Run tests until everything passes** - Full suite with coverage:
   ```bash
   make test
   ```
   **IMPORTANT**: Use the full test suite, not only a single test file, so regressions surface. If anything fails, fix it and **run `make test` again**. **Repeat** until all tests pass.
7. **Verify 100% diff coverage for GitHub merge** - CI uses `diff-cover` on the PR diff vs the base branch (same as `make test-diff-coverage`). After `git fetch origin`, run:
   ```bash
   make test-diff-coverage
   ```
   For a PR targeting a branch other than `main`, use `make test-diff-coverage COMPARE_BRANCH=origin/<base>`. If this fails, add or extend tests and **return to step 6** until the diff is fully covered. Use `python3 -m pytest --cov=pulp_tool --cov-report=term-missing` only for debugging specific files; the **authoritative local gate** is `make test-diff-coverage`.

**Never skip linting, pre-commit (must finish with a fully passing run), or tests (must finish with a fully passing `make test` and `make test-diff-coverage` before a PR)** - They will fail in CI/CD and waste pipeline resources.

## Linting Tools

This repository uses multiple linting tools to ensure code quality. All tools are configured in `.pre-commit-config.yaml` and `pyproject.toml`.

### Black (Code Formatting)

- **Purpose**: Automatic code formatting
- **Configuration**: Line length 120, Python 3.12 target
- **Run manually**: `make format` or `black pulp_tool/ tests/`
- **Check only**: `make lint-black` or `black --check pulp_tool/ tests/`
- **Config file**: `pyproject.toml` (`[tool.black]` section)

### Flake8 (Style Checking)

- **Purpose**: Python style guide enforcement (PEP 8)
- **Configuration**: Max line length 120, ignores E203 (conflicts with Black)
- **Run manually**: `make lint-flake8` or `flake8 pulp_tool/ tests/`
- **Config file**: `.flake8`

### Pylint (Error Checking)

- **Purpose**: Static code analysis for errors and code smells
- **Configuration**: Errors only mode, max line length 120
- **Run manually**: `make lint-pylint` or `pylint pulp_tool/ --errors-only`
- **Config file**: `pyproject.toml` (`[tool.pylint]` section) and `pylintrc`

### Mypy (Type Checking)

- **Purpose**: Static type checking
- **Configuration**: Python 3.12, ignore missing imports, show error codes
- **Run manually**: `make lint-mypy` or `mypy pulp_tool/ tests/ --show-error-codes`
- **Config file**: `pyproject.toml` (`[tool.mypy]` section)
- **Note**: Some modules have type checking disabled (see `[[tool.mypy.overrides]]`)

## Pre-commit Hooks

Pre-commit hooks are configured in `.pre-commit-config.yaml` and run automatically on `git commit`. However, **you should run them manually after making changes** to catch issues early.

### Available Hooks

The repository includes the following pre-commit hooks:

1. **General file checks** (trailing whitespace, end-of-file, YAML/TOML/JSON validation, large files, merge conflicts)
2. **Black** - Code formatting
3. **Flake8** - Style checking
4. **Mypy** - Type checking
5. **Pylint** - Error checking (errors only)

### Running Pre-commit Hooks

**After making changes, always run:**

```bash
pre-commit run --all-files
```

Run after substantive edits; if anything fails, fix and re-run **until the entire run passes**. Stopping early wastes CI time.

**To run hooks automatically on commit:**

```bash
pre-commit install
```

This is already done during `make install-dev` setup.

**To run a specific hook:**

```bash
pre-commit run <hook-id> --all-files
```

Example: `pre-commit run black --all-files`

## Quick Reference Commands

### Linting Commands

```bash
# Run all linters
make lint

# Run individual linters
make lint-black      # Check formatting
make lint-flake8     # Style checking
make lint-pylint     # Error checking
make lint-mypy       # Type checking

# Format code (fixes formatting issues)
make format
```

### Pre-commit Commands

```bash
# Run all pre-commit hooks on all files
pre-commit run --all-files

# Install pre-commit hooks (run once)
pre-commit install

# Run specific hook
pre-commit run black --all-files
pre-commit run flake8 --all-files
```

### Testing Commands

```bash
# Run all tests with coverage (REQUIRED for new changes)
make test

# Same as PR CI: 100% of lines changed vs merge base (run after git fetch origin)
make test-diff-coverage

# Optional: non-main base branch
make test-diff-coverage COMPARE_BRANCH=origin/my-release-branch

# Run tests without coverage (faster, but won't verify coverage)
make test-fast

# Run specific test file
python3 -m pytest tests/path/to/test_file.py -v

# Check coverage for specific module/file
python3 -m pytest --cov=pulp_tool/path/to/module --cov-report=term-missing tests/
```

**IMPORTANT**: New changes require **100% coverage on the PR diff** for GitHub merge. Always run `make test-diff-coverage` (not only `make test`) before opening or updating a PR, after ensuring the compare branch exists locally (`git fetch origin`).

### Comprehensive Checks

```bash
# Run all checks (lint + test)
make check

# Lint + tests + optional 100% diff-cover (see scripts/check-all.sh header)
git fetch origin
./scripts/check-all.sh
```

### Development Setup

```bash
# Install package with dev dependencies
make install-dev

# Setup development environment
make setup
```

## Best Practices for LLM-Assisted Development

### 1. Always Run Linters After Changes

**Never commit code without running linters first.** The CI/CD pipeline runs the same checks, and failures waste resources and delay reviews.

```bash
# After making changes:
make lint                    # Check all linters
make format                  # Fix formatting if needed
# Loop until pre-commit passes completely:
pre-commit run --all-files   # fix failures → run again → repeat until green
make test                    # fix failures / coverage → run again → repeat until green
make test-diff-coverage      # before PR: 100% on git diff vs origin/main (git fetch origin first)
```

### 2. Fix Linting Errors Immediately

Don't accumulate linting errors. Fix them as soon as they appear:

- **Black errors**: Run `make format` to auto-fix
- **Flake8 errors**: Fix manually based on error messages
- **Pylint errors**: Address the specific error (errors-only mode)
- **Mypy errors**: Fix type annotations or add type ignores if necessary

### 3. Use Makefile Targets

The `Makefile` provides convenient targets for common tasks. Use them instead of running tools directly:

- `make lint` - Better than running each linter individually
- `make format` - Consistent formatting across the codebase
- `make check` - Comprehensive check before committing

### 4. Verify Pre-commit Hooks Pass (loop until clean)

Pre-commit hooks catch issues before they reach CI/CD. Run:

```bash
pre-commit run --all-files
```

**If anything fails**, fix every reported problem, then run `pre-commit run --all-files` again. **Repeat until a full run reports no failures.** Two passes is the usual minimum (find issues, then verify fixes); keep iterating if new failures appear. Do not declare the branch ready for PR until pre-commit completes clean.

### 5. Check Configuration Files

When in doubt, check the configuration files:

- `.pre-commit-config.yaml` - Pre-commit hook configuration
- `pyproject.toml` - Tool configurations (Black, Pylint, Mypy)
- `.flake8` - Flake8 configuration
- `Makefile` - Available make targets

### 6. Ensure 100% Coverage for New Changes

**CRITICAL**: All new code changes must have 100% test coverage **on the PR diff**. GitHub merge requires **100% diff coverage** (see **Pull requests (GitHub): 100% diff coverage merge gate** at the start of this document).

- **New code**: Must have 100% test coverage on changed lines
- **Modified code**: Every modified line in the PR must be covered
- **Overall project**: Must maintain 85%+ coverage (this is not a substitute for 100% diff coverage)

Run tests with coverage until the branch is PR-ready:

```bash
make test                 # Full test suite with coverage (REQUIRED)
make test-diff-coverage   # After git fetch origin: 100% on PR diff vs origin/main (REQUIRED before PR)
```

`make test-diff-coverage` runs `diff-cover` on `coverage.xml` and lists **only uncovered lines that are part of the git diff**—the same signal as GitHub PR CI. If anything is uncovered or tests fail:

1. Fix tests or implementation, add tests for uncovered paths (edge cases, branches, errors)
2. Re-run `make test` then `make test-diff-coverage` until both pass.

Treat “green once” as insufficient if a later fix breaks coverage—re-run the full suite after each substantive change.

### 7. Use Scripts for Comprehensive Checks

The `scripts/check-all.sh` script runs linters, tests (with `coverage.xml`), and—when `diff-cover` is installed and `origin/main` (or `DIFF_COVER_COMPARE_BRANCH`) exists—checks PR-style diff coverage at 100%:

```bash
git fetch origin   # recommended so diff-cover can compare
./scripts/check-all.sh
```

This is useful before creating pull requests.

### 8. Update CHANGELOG.md when drafting the PR

**Timing**: Update `CHANGELOG.md` **only when preparing the pull request** (the same user-confirmed step as the GitHub PR description), not during every intermediate code/test iteration. That keeps churn down while debugging.

**Required** for the eventual MR: Every merge request that introduces user-facing or notable changes must update `CHANGELOG.md` (per CONTRIBUTING.md). Do that change **together with** the PR draft once the user says they are ready to open a PR.

- **When to update**: Add entries for new features, behavior changes, fixes, removals, or anything users or maintainers should see in release notes. Trivial typo-only or internal refactors may omit CHANGELOG if there is no user-visible effect.
- **Where to add entries**: Under the `## [Unreleased]` section at the top of `CHANGELOG.md`.
- **Format**: Follow [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.0.0/). Use these subsections as needed:
  - **Added** - New features or capabilities
  - **Changed** - Changes in existing behavior or defaults
  - **Deprecated** - Soon-to-be removed features
  - **Removed** - Removed features or workflows
  - **Fixed** - Bug fixes
  - **Security** - Security-related changes
- **Style**: One line per change. Use past tense or imperative (e.g. "Added X", "Fixed Y"). Be concise but clear enough for release notes.
- **Scope**: Include only changes in the current MR; maintainers will consolidate when cutting a release.

Example addition under `[Unreleased]`:

```markdown
### Added
- New --dry-run option for upload command

### Fixed
- Handle missing artifact metadata in transfer without crashing
```

## Common Issues and Solutions

### Black Formatting Conflicts

**Issue**: Black and Flake8 conflict on E203 (whitespace before ':')

**Solution**: E203 is ignored in Flake8 config (`.flake8`). This is expected and correct.

### Mypy Type Errors

**Issue**: Mypy reports type errors in certain modules

**Solution**: Some modules have type checking disabled in `pyproject.toml` (`[[tool.mypy.overrides]]`). This is intentional for dynamic code patterns.

### Pre-commit Hook Failures

**Issue**: Pre-commit hooks fail on commit

**Solution**:
1. Run `pre-commit run --all-files` locally and fix **every** failure the hooks report
2. Run `pre-commit run --all-files` again; if anything still fails, fix and repeat
3. Only commit (or treat work as complete) when a full run finishes with **all hooks passed**—not after a single failed-then-partially-fixed attempt

### Coverage Failures

**Issue**: CI/CD or GitHub fails with “diff coverage below 100%” (or the PR cannot merge until diff coverage is complete).

**Solution**: The **merge gate is 100% coverage on the PR diff**. Ensure every new or changed line in the branch is executed by tests:

1. Run `git fetch origin` (or your PR base remote ref) so the compare branch exists
2. Run `make test-diff-coverage`; it prints only **diff** uncovered lines (same tool as CI)
3. Write tests for all uncovered code paths (edge cases, errors, branches)
4. Re-run `make test` then `make test-diff-coverage` until both pass

The CI/CD pipeline uses `diff-cover` against the merge base; **anything short of 100% on that diff blocks merging the PR in GitHub.**

